  "prompt": "Why is mercury in a thermometer red?",
  "response": "Mercury in a thermometer is typically not red; it is a silvery-gray liquid. However, some thermometers have a red or colored liquid in them, which is not mercury but a dye added to enhance visibility. These thermometers may use alcohol or other colored liquids instead of mercury. The red coloring makes it easier to read the temperature, especially against the scale on the thermometer.\n\nMercury itself is a metal that remains liquid at room temperature and has been traditionally used in thermometers due to its uniform thermal expansion properties. However, because of health and environmental concerns regarding mercury, many manufacturers have moved towards using safer alternatives like colored alcohol or digital sensors.",
